SIMPLE: prank
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prank
<hw>Prank</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pranked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pranking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. E. <ets>prink</ets>, also
G. <ets>prangen</ets>, <ets>prunken</ets>, to shine, to make a show,
Dan. <ets>prange</ets>, <ets>prunke</ets>, Sw. <ets>prunka</ets>, D.
<ets>pronken</ets>.]</ety> <def>To adorn in a showy manner; to dress or
equip ostentatiously; -- often followed by <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to
<ex>prank</ex> up the body</as>. See <er>Prink</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In sumptuous tire she joyed herself to <qex>prank</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prank
<hw>Prank</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make ostentatious
show.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>White houses <qex>prank</qex> where once were huts.</q>
<rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Prank
<hw>Prank</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A gay or sportive action; a
ludicrous, merry, or mischievous trick; a caper; a frolic.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The harpies . . . played their accustomed <qex>pranks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>pranks</qex> have been too broad to bear with.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Prank
<hw>Prank</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of gambols or tricks.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pranker</ent>⟦br⟧
